              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25183427#p25183427" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">t1oracle</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25183371#p25183371" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Wickwick</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Can't we do a bit better than &quot;a coin flip&quot; determines an El Nino or a La Nina?<br /><br />There is SOME collection of forcing variables  that lead to one or the other. And not knowing those variables and the temperature of the Pacific appears to have a pretty large impact on our ability to predict atmospheric temperatures.</div><br />If you can do us all a favor and measure the exact temperature and velocity of every atom within the planet Earth and feed that data into a sufficiently powerful super computer, the rest of us will thank you greatly for giving us the tools for near flawless weather prediction.</div><br />I work in weather prediction and I just don't think this is true. For one thing, there will probably never exist computers with sufficient power to do that, and, even if they did, very tiny variations that are unaccounted for end up making a compounding difference as time advances. So weather prediction is inaccurate, and will always be inaccurate, and because of that weather cannot be accurately predicted way into the future.

              

              
              
