              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25183405#p25183405" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Pysgard</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Perhaps La Nina might be part of the broader system response, a natural damper on temps, and indeed, a mechanism transporting heat into deep ocean waters.</div><br /><br />It sort of is the latter (see <a href="http://arstechnica.com/science/2013/04/oceans-continue-to-warm-especially-the-deeps/" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">here</a>), but the former is uncertain. For example, a <a href="http://www.nature.com/nclimate/journal/v3/n9/full/nclimate1936.html" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">paper</a> I just saw today shows that El Nino/La Nina became more variable in the latter part of the 20th century. No sign of a La Nina bias, though.

              

              
              
            </div>
