            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25183723#p25183723" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">ooostephen</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It hasn't warmed for 15+ years, but the globe is still warming?  <br />The salient point is that none of the models allowed for greater than a 10yr pause in temps, with a 95% certainty.   Those models were clearly wrong, and all their predictions go out the window.</div><br /><br />Actually, if you account for variables that affect the atmospheric temperature and that the models were not intended to predict (El Nino/La Nina cycles, solar cycles, volcanic eruptions) then not only has the atmospheric warming continued unabated, the models are bang-on.<br /><br />In other words, any conclusion (for or against the AGW hypothesis or specific models) is invalid unless you determine what the temperature <span style="font-style: italic">would</span> have been without the effect of e.g. the prolonged solar minimum. As it turns out without that we would be even hotter.  As predicted.

              

              
              
            </div>
