          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Not to wax nostalgic on y'all, but Entergy has announced it will <a href="http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/C-Entergy_opts_to_shut_Vermont_Yankee-2708134.html" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">shutdown Vermont Yankee</a> at the end of next year. This 600 MW BWR supplies nearly three-fourths of Vermont's electricity. Vermont Yankee went online in November 1972 and recently received a 20 year extension from NRC for its operating license. But it is not economically competitive with cut-rate natural gas and irrationally subsidized wind. Replacing VY's 600 MW(e) with natural gas will emit 2.5 million tonnes CO2 <span style="font-style: italic">each year</span>.<br /><br /> 600 MW(e) with 90% capacity factor would need 810 2MW wind turbines at 33% capacity factor. NPP and wind both need 100% backup -- with nuclear you need it much less often but for longer intervals when you do.   <br /><br />In three years levelized cost of wind will be about $97/MWh, CCGT about $63/MWh, 2009 dollars. Wind's current $22/MWh pre-tax PTC makes the two LCOE sorta kinda equivalent (as it amounts to an after-tax $33). These levelized costs are marginal costs of wind at its current low penetration of 3.4%. Cost of wind are projected to increase by <span style="font-style: italic">at least</span> 50% at total renewable penetration of 72%.  But no one is planning for that.<br /><br />Sources: <a href="http://www.skepticalscience.com/true-cost-of-coal-power.html" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">True Cost of Coal Power</a> and <a href="http://www.nrel.gov/analysis/re_futures/" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">NREL Renewable Energy Futures Study</a>

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
